{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":205176,"duration_api_ms":205108,"num_turns":31,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"1ba01028-da6d-4a6b-b4a3-e6809d5e571c","total_cost_usd":1.0607432500000002,"usage":{"input_tokens":20,"cache_creation_input_tokens":59575,"cache_read_input_tokens":927499,"output_tokens":8982,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":59575,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":20,"outputTokens":8982,"cacheReadInputTokens":927499,"cacheCreationInputTokens":59575,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.0607432500000002,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed all changes across 7 files: retry_policy.rs (jitter re-cap fix), process_backend.rs (timeout enforcement, exit code classification, spawn ENOENT guard), agent_execution/service.rs (saturating_add), engine.rs (pre-backoff snapshot persistence, derive_resume_state retry tracking), and test files. The implementation is solid and correctly addresses the core objectives: increased retry limits (5/3/3), hard timeout enforcement via tokio::time::timeout in spawn_and_wait, exit 127 → BinaryNotFound (terminal), signal kills → TransportFailure with logging, exponential backoff with jitter, and crash-safe resume that preserves attempt counts. The pre-backoff snapshot persistence is well-designed with best-effort semantics. No critical bugs found; only minor concerns noted below.","amendments":[{"body":"In `derive_resume_state` (engine.rs ~line 5843), the `CycleAdvanced` handler does not clear stale entries from `retryable_failed_attempts` for prior cycles. While functionally correct (the HashMap key includes cycle number, so old entries won't match new-cycle lookups), the entries accumulate across cycles and are never reclaimed. In runs with many remediation cycles, this is a bounded but unnecessary memory growth. Add `retryable_failed_attempts.retain(|&(_, c), _| c >= current_cycle);` after updating `current_cycle` in the CycleAdvanced handler, matching the pattern used by CompletionRoundAdvanced's `.clear()`.","rationale":"Consistency with CompletionRoundAdvanced which does clear retry history, and defense against long-running projects that cycle many times."},{"body":"The `apply_jitter` function (retry_policy.rs:134-143) uses `SystemTime::now().subsec_nanos() % 1000` as a randomness source. On systems where the clock resolution is coarser than 1μs (e.g., some VMs or containers), multiple calls within the same millisecond will produce identical jitter values, defeating the thundering-herd mitigation the jitter is designed to provide. Consider using `thread_rng()` from the `rand` crate (already a transitive dependency) or at minimum `Instant::now()` which is monotonic, or mix in the attempt number to ensure distinct values across consecutive retries.","rationale":"The jitter's purpose is to stagger concurrent retries across multiple backends. If all backends retry at the same moment and get the same jitter, the backoff provides no stagger benefit."},{"body":"The timeout test `clean_timeout_teardown_yields_timeout_without_warning` (tests/unit/process_backend_test.rs) uses `start_paused = true` with `current_thread` runtime but relies on a real OS process (`sleep 99999`) that blocks the child wait. Tokio's auto-advance only fires when all tasks are pending on timers, but `active_child.wait()` is an OS I/O operation that won't trigger auto-advance. If this test passes, it's because the process I/O futures (stdout/stderr EOF) complete and the remaining `wait()` is the only non-timer pending task — but this behavior is implementation-dependent and fragile across Tokio versions. Consider adding a brief comment explaining why `start_paused` works here, or use a real 2-second timeout without `start_paused` to avoid coupling to Tokio internals.","rationale":"A test that accidentally depends on Tokio runtime internals can break silently on upgrades, turning a passing test into a flaky one."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"124eeede-0f24-41a9-90d9-1911f7ac15b7"}
